&lt;p&gt;We&#39;re seeking a Robotics Software Engineer who thrives on hard systems problems. Welding is where we started — but the mission is broader: robots that sense, plan, and act to take on skilled manual work. You&#39;ll write modern C++ across the full robotics stack — perception and scanning, motion and task planning, real-time execution, and closed-loop control — and see your code run on live robotic cells doing real work. You&#39;ll also help us advance our planning and control by combining classical techniques with modern learning-based methods, making our robots faster, smarter, and more capable. If you&#39;re ready to take on the hardest problems with the best team on the planet, bring your expertise and enthusiasm.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2&gt;What You’ll Do&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Build motion and trajectory planning for a variety of task goals — from patterned and adaptive, sensor-driven motions to resource-aware sequencing that coordinates multiple robots working the same part.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Develop kinematics, reachability, and motion planning — inverse kinematics and trajectory planning for robotic manipulators — and validate plans so motion is collision-free and executable.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Build the real-time control and feedback loops that keep the robot on target as it works — trajectory correction, feature tracking, and camera-based visual servoing.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Extend our robots beyond fixed workcells to mobile platforms — localization, mapping, and navigation so a moving robot can find its work and hold position while it acts.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Own the driver layer that connects to robot hardware — streaming motion commands to the robot controller in real time and abstracting sensors, scanners, and cameras behind clean, reliable interfaces.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Advance the stack with learning-based methods and simulation — reinforcement learning, learned planners, and sim-to-real training, alongside classical approaches.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
